content.text: What is a unit for stress?
A \(\mathsf{kgm}^{- 1}\mathsf{s}^{- 2}\) B \(\mathsf{kgm}^{- 2}\mathsf{s}^{- 2}\) C \(\mathsf{Nm}^{- 1}\) D \(\mathsf{Nm}\)
Physical quantities can be classed as vectors or as scalars
Which pair of quantities consists of two vectors?
A kinetic energy and force
B momentum and time
C velocity and electric field strength
D weight and temperature
Two dogs pull a sledge along an icy track, as shown
Dog X pulls with a force of 200N at an angle of \(65^{\circ}\) to the front edge of the sledge. Dog Y pulls with a force of 120N at an angle of \(45^{\circ}\) to the front edge of the sledge
What is the resultant forward force on the sledge exerted by the two dogs?
A 80N B 170N C 270N D 320N

In the circuit shown, an analogue ammeter is to be recalibrated as a thermometer. The ammeter is connected in series with a thermistor. The thermistor is a component with a resistance that varies with temperature. The graph shows how the resistance \(R\) of the thermistor changes with temperature \(T\)
Which diagram could represent the temperature scale on the ammeter?
The sides of a cube are measured with calipers
The measured length of each side is \((30.0 \pm 0.1) \text{mm}\)
The measurements are used to calculate the volume of the cube
What is the percentage uncertainty in the calculated value of the volume?
A tennis ball falls freely, in air, from the top of a tall building
Which graph best represents the variation with time \(t\) of the distance \(s\) fallen?
The graph shows the variation with mass of the weight of objects on a particular planet
What is the value of the acceleration of free fall on the planet?
The momentum of a car of mass \(m\) increases from \(p_{1}\) to \(p_{2}\)
What is the increase in the kinetic energy of the car?
The spheres stick together on impact
Two similar spheres, each of mass \(m\) and travelling with speed \(v\), are moving towards each other
The spheres have a head-on elastic collision
Which statement is correct?
A horizontal metal bar PQ of length 50.0 cm is hinged at end P. The diagram shows the metal bar viewed from above
Two forces of 16.0N and 5.0N are in the horizontal plane and act on end Q as shown in the diagram
What is the total moment about P due to the two forces?
A 1.5N m B 4.4N m C 6.5N m D 9.4N m
Blocks P, Q, R and S are made from material of the same density. Block T is made from a material of twice the density of the material of the other blocks
The cross-sectional area and height of each of the blocks are shown
Which two blocks exert the same pressure on the ground?
A P and T B Q and R C Q and S D S and T
Two parallel forces, each of magnitude \(F\) , act on a rod of length \(5d\)
Which diagram shows the positions of the two forces that will produce the largest torque on the rod?
Liquids X and Y are stored in large open tanks. Liquid X has a density of \(800 \text{kg} \text{m}^{-3}\) and liquid Y has a density of \(1200 \text{kg} \text{m}^{-3}\)
At which depths are the pressures equal?

A train of mass \(3.3 \times 10^{6} \text{kg}\) is moving at a constant speed up a slope inclined at an angle of \(0.64^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. The engine of the train is producing a useful output power of \(14 \text{MW}\)
Assume that there are no frictional forces opposing the motion of the train
What is the speed of the train?
A cannon-ball of mass \(3.50 \text{kg}\) is fired at a speed of \(22.0 \text{m} \text{s}^{-1}\) from a gun on a ship at a height of \(6.00 \text{m}\) above sea level
The total energy of the cannon-ball is the sum of the gravitational potential energy relative to the surface of the sea and the kinetic energy
What is the total energy of the cannon-ball as it leaves the gun?
An aircraft travels at a constant velocity of \(90 \text{m} \text{s}^{-1}\) in horizontal flight. The diagram shows some of the forces acting on the aircraft
The mass of the aircraft is \(2000 \text{kg}\)
What is the power produced by the thrust force?
B 13W
C 30W
D 50W
An electrical generator is started at time zero. The total electrical energy generated during the first 5 seconds is shown in the graph
What is the maximum electrical power generated at any instant during these first 5 seconds?
The diagram shows a wire of diameter \(D\) and length \(L\) that is firmly clamped at one end between two blocks of wood. A load is applied to the wire which extends its length by \(x\)
A second wire is made of the same material, but of diameter \(2D\) and length \(3L\). Both wires obey Hooke's law
What is the extension of the second wire when the same load is applied?
Two wires, one made of brass and the other of steel, are stretched in an experiment. Both wires obey Hooke's law during this experiment
The Young modulus for brass is less than the Young modulus for steel
Which graph shows how the stress varies with strain for both wires in this experiment?
A transverse progressive wave is set up on a string
The graph shows the variation with time of displacement for a point on this string
The separation XY on the graph represents the ......1...... of the wave
X and Y have equal ......2
Which words correctly complete gaps 1 and 2?
Which region of the electromagnetic spectrum includes waves with a frequency of \(10^{7} \text{MHz}\)?
A infra-red waves
B radio waves
C ultraviolet waves
D X-rays
A longitudinal wave has vibrations parallel to the direction of transfer of energy by the wave
The wave can be represented on a graph showing the variation of the displacement of the particles with distance from the source
Which point on the graph is the centre of a compression?
What can be deduced from a table of wavelengths of the waves in the electromagnetic spectrum?
A Green light has a shorter wavelength than X-rays
B Red light has a shorter wavelength than green light
C The wavelength range for radio waves is less than that for infra-red waves
D The wavelength range for X-rays is less than that for radio waves
A binary star consists of two stars rotating around a common centre. Light from one of the stars is observed on the Earth
The observed frequency of the light varies between a minimum frequency \(f_{\mathrm{min}}\) and a maximum frequency \(f_{\mathrm{max}}\), as shown
The rate of rotation of the binary star increases
What is the change to \(f_{\mathrm{max}}\) and the change to \(f_{\mathrm{min}}\)?
A teacher sets up the apparatus shown to demonstrate a double-slit interference pattern on the screen
Which change to the apparatus will increase the fringe spacing?
**A** decreasing the distance \(p\)
**B** decreasing the distance \(q\)
**C** decreasing the distance \(r\)
**D** decreasing the wavelength of the light
The diagram shows two sources of waves \(\mathsf{S}_1\) and \(\mathsf{S}_2\) . The sources oscillate with a phase difference of \(180^{\circ}\)
The sources each generate a wave of wavelength \(2.0 \text{cm}\). Each source produces a wave that has amplitude \(x_0\) when it reaches point P
What is the amplitude of the oscillation at P?
A pipe, closed at one end, has a loudspeaker at the open end. A stationary sound wave is formed in the air within the pipe with an antinode at the open end of the pipe
The length of the pipe is \(0.85 \text{m}\)
The speed of sound in air is \(340 \text{m s}^{-1}\)
Which frequency of sound from the loudspeaker would **not** produce a stationary wave?
A particle has a charge of \(+2.0 \text{mC}\) and is in a vertical uniform electric field. An electric force of \(1.0 \times 10^{-2} \text{N}\) acts upwards on the particle
What is the electric field strength?
**A** \(0.20 \text{V m}^{-1}\) downwards
**B** \(0.20 \text{V m}^{-1}\) upwards
**C** \(5.0 \text{V m}^{-1}\) downwards
**D** \(5.0 \text{V m}^{-1}\) upwards
A charged particle is in the electric field between two horizontal metal plates connected to a battery, as shown. There is a force \(F\) on the particle due to the electric field
The separation of the plates is doubled
What is the new force on the particle?
the number of atoms per unit volume of the metal
The current \(I\) in a metal wire is given by the expression shown
What does the symbol \(n\) represent?

The circuit diagrams show two lamps X and Y each connected to a cell. The current in lamp X is \(0.50\mathsf{A}\) and its resistance is \(9.6\mathsf{\Omega}\) . The current in lamp Y is \(3.0\mathsf{A}\) and its resistance is \(1.2\mathsf{\Omega}\)
What is the ratio \(\frac{\text{power in lamp } \mathsf{X}}{\text{power in lamp } \mathsf{Y}}?\)
A cylindrical piece of a soft, electrically-conducting material has resistance \(R\) . It is rolled out so that its length is doubled but its volume stays constant
What is its new resistance?
The sum of the electrical currents into a point in a circuit is equal to the sum of the currents out of the point
Which statement is correct?
A This is Kirchhoff's first law, which results from the conservation of charge
B This is Kirchhoff's first law, which results from the conservation of energy
C This is Kirchhoff's second law, which results from the conservation of charge
D This is Kirchhoff's second law, which results from the conservation of energy
In the circuit shown, the batteries have negligible internal resistance
What are the values of the currents \(I_{1}, I_{2}\) and \(I_{3}\)?
A battery of electromotive force (e.m.f.) 6.0V and negligible internal resistance is connected to three resistors as shown
Each resistor has a resistance of 4.0k
What is the current in resistor X?

A uniform resistance wire XY of length \(100 \text{cm}\) is connected in series with a cell L. Another cell M is connected in series with resistors of resistances \(5.00 \Omega\), \(10.0 \Omega\) and \(15.0 \Omega\)
The potential difference (p.d.) between P and Q is balanced against \(12.5 \text{cm}\) of the resistance wire, so that the ammeter reads zero
The p.d. across the other resistors is then balanced against other lengths of the resistance wire
Which balanced lengths of resistance wire correspond to the connection points given in the table?

content.text: A motor is required to operate at a distance of \(800 \text{m}\) from its power supply. The motor requires a potential difference (p.d.) of \(16.0 \text{V}\) and a current of \(0.60 \text{A}\) to operate
Two wires are used to supply power to the motor as shown
The resistance of each of these wires is \(0.0050 \Omega\) per metre
What is the minimum output p.d. of the power supply?
Which elementary particle is a lepton?
A proton
B neutron
C electron
D quark
How many down quarks are in a nucleus of hydrogen-3, \(^3_1H?\)
A 2 B 3 C 4 D 5
What is the correct equation for \(\beta^{+}\) decay?
A neutron \(\rightarrow\) proton + electron + electron antineutrino
B neutron \(\rightarrow\) proton + electron + electron neutrino
C proton \(\rightarrow\) neutron + positron + electron antineutrino
D proton \(\rightarrow\) neutron + positron + electron neutrino
